{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation*, Volume I (Chapter 21)** argues precisely this point.[^1]\n\nComte contends that institutions such as foundling hospitals (where women can deliver children free of charge), homes for unwed mothers (receiving and maintaining illegitimate children at public or charitable expense), and asylums for \"repentant\" prostitutes (providing shelter, food, clothing, and efforts at social reintegration) undermine natural moral penalties by easing the physical, emotional, and social consequences of vice (e.g., shame, poverty, disease, child-rearing burdens, and abandonment) borne by the guilty party alone, while leaving the immediate pleasures of vice untouched. This imbalance encourages vice's spread, harming the innocent by multiplying impunity's costs without repression's benefits.[^2][^3][^4][^5][^6]\n\nThe key passage comparing such institutions to breaking prison doors reads:\n\n> [p-b31bb4] A vice naturally produces for him who has contracted it diverse physical pains, such as those that result from misery; it produces diverse kinds of diseases; it produces, moreover, moral pains, contempt, abandonment, antipathy, the sorrow of seeing one’s line extinguished or decline; it produces intellectual incapacity and the evils that accompany it. Now, any act by which an individual, a society, or a government diminishes the publicity, intensity, duration, or certainty of any of these pains, is an attack on good customs. Such an act has the effect of weakening the only guarantee that each of us possesses against the vices of others; **it acts, with regard to vicious habits, as would act, with regard to the actions that authority represses, the existence of a society that, out of humanity, made it a duty to go and break down the doors of prisons.** A few examples will make this truth more perceptible.[^7]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, ch. 21 (“De l’action des lois de la morale, et des obstacles que cette action rencontre quelquefois dans cell”), [chapter](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-cd2fdf](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-cd2fdf) (foundling hospitals).\n\n[^3]: Ibid., [p-ff6980](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-ff6980) (illegitimate children/maintenance for unwed mothers).\n\n[^4]: Ibid., [p-682ecc](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-682ecc) (treatment of diseases from vice).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., [p-273291](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-273291) (asylums for \"repentant\" prostitutes).\n\n[^6]: See also [p-33355b](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-33355b) (prostitution's natural penalties).\n\n[^7]: Ibid., [p-b31bb4](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-b31bb4).",
